Hey, all of you, stop for a minute. This thread is going off base. Please refocus. If you don't, how in the heck can I pick a fight or drop one of my pearls of wisdom on you?<br><br>
That's a joke brothers.  If anything that is common to vietnam vets, it is that THEY DON'T KNOW HOW TO LAUGH about things they should.  I know the bush was bad, but 30 years later you got to have a sense of humor, or my associates and their butterfly nets will snag you.  Understand?  I don't mean to insult, or to laugh about fire fights and trip wires, only to tell you that LIFE GOES ON, and you have to deal with it.  PERIOD.<br><br>
Tom Dier, you dogged me and now you talk about the right of protest, when I, the &quot;moral&quot; protestor challeged you to a reply and you declined by silence?  By the way, your civil war comments I think are perfectly stated.<br><br>
Jeff- Your thinking and historical information is great, but is it appropriate for this site?  God Damn, you need a literary agent, not a PBS site.  Tanker's suggestion about back channeling it was on the mark. I found myself taking notes reading your post. Gee, something about reading a computer screen and taking notes seems like an oxymoron, any one else agree?<br><br>
DocDel as usual keeps a cool thread.<br><br>
I might as well stir up the pot, as I am off to do, and righteously accused of doing with this: (1) I don't think there is a single reason or policy about why we got into Nam and ended up with 56,000 dead American lads. As strange as that is, and I trace it back to JFK, I think it shows that our government can and did get all fucked up about priorities, domino theories, Kissenger nonsense, and blundered along with NO REAL GAME PLAN, until Nixon finally decided to end it. Probably the only great thing he did. Peace with Honor (my ass). It was just Stop Killing American Lads.  Remember, we used to think commies were behind every rock and sampans would soon attack California.  Amazing how 30 years later we are ALL so wise.<br><br>
Oh, a note for the record, and the e mails I get. I leave my shrink shingle at the office every day, the &quot;doc&quot; is a part of me and I can't turn it off.  The &quot;shrink&quot; part of me I can. So on this site, I am just the protestor-C.O. who also survived, and ALSO made a contribution, however small in comparison, to his country.  And I will forever post critical comments that push all of you into critical thinking, CAUSE I CAN'T HELP IT.  OK?<br><br>
